# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ktor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ktor/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:ktor/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:ktor/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:ktor/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:ktor/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:ktor/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:ktor/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:ktor/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:ktor/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:ktor/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:ktor/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:ktor/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:ktor/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:ktor/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:ktor/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:ktor/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:ktor/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:ktor/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:ktor/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:ktor/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:ktor/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:ktor/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:ktor/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:ktor/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:ktor/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:ktor/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:ktor/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:ktor/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:ktor/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:ktor/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:ktor/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:ktor/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:ktor/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:ktor/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:ktor/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:ktor/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:ktor/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:ktor/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:ktor/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] One of Kotlin's stated goals is to compile as quickly as Java.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] In February 2012, JetBrains open-sourced the project under the Apache 2 license.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains expected Kotlin to drive sales of IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.0 was released on 15 February 2016, which is considered the first officially stable release, and JetBrains has committed to long-term backwards compatibility starting with this version.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] At Google I/O 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced that Kotlin is now its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Development lead Andrey Breslav has said that Kotlin is designed to be an industrial-strength object-oriented language, a "better language" than Java, and still fully interoperable with Java code, allowing companies to make a gradual migration from Java to Kotlin.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] For example, `@file:JvmName("JavaClassName")`.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin provides the following keywords to restrict visibility for top-level declarations (such as classes) and for class members: `public`, `internal`, `protected`, and `private`.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin distinguishes between nullable and non-nullable data types.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] All nullable objects must be declared with a "?" postfix after the type name.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin supports higher-order functions and anonymous functions, or **lambdas**.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] If a lambda takes parameters, they are declared within the braces and followed by the -> operator.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin Multiplatform enables a single codebase to target multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, the web, Android, and iOS.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Compose Multiplatform is a multiplatform UI framework based on Jetpack Compose.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] It is Jetpack Compose for Android ported to Windows, macOS, Linux, web, and iOS.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] For example, the Text composable function displays a text label on the screen.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] In 2018, Kotlin was the fastest-growing language on GitHub, with 2.6 times as many developers as in 2017.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] It is the fourth-most-loved programming language according to the 2020 Stack Overflow Developer Survey.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin was also awarded the O'Reilly Open Source Software Conference Breakout Award for 2019.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] A large number of companies in various industries use Kotlin, including Google, Amazon Web Services, Netflix and McDonald's.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] When Kotlin was announced as an official Android development language at Google I/O in May 2017, it became the third language fully supported for Android, after Java and C++.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] As of 2020, Kotlin was the most widely used language on Android, with Google estimating that 70% of the top 1,000 apps on the Play Store were written in Kotlin.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Google itself had 60 apps written in Kotlin, including Maps and Drive.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Many Android apps, such as Google Home, were in the process of migrating to Kotlin and therefore use both Kotlin and Java.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin on Android is seen as beneficial for its null-safety and features that make code shorter and more readable.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Ktor is a JetBrains Kotlin-first framework for building server and client applications.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] The Spring Framework officially added Kotlin support with version 5, on 4 January 2017.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] To further support Kotlin, Spring has translated all its documentation into Kotlin and added built-in support for many Kotlin-specific features, such as coroutines.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] In 2020, JetBrains found in a survey of developers who use Kotlin that 56% used it for mobile apps, while 47% used it for a web backend.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Just over a third of all Kotlin developers said they were migrating from another language.
[src:ktor/kotlin-programming-language] Most Kotlin users targeted Android (or the JVM), with only 6% using Kotlin Native.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains offers a variety of integrated development environments (IDEs), such as IntelliJ IDEA, PyCharm, Rider, WebStorm and CLion.
[src:ktor/ktor] It also created the Kotlin programming language in 2011, which can run in a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains, initially called IntelliJ Software, was founded in 2000 in Prague by three Russian software developers: Sergey Dmitriev, Valentin Kipyatkov and Eugene Belyaev.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company's first product was IntelliJ Renamer, a tool for code refactoring in Java.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2012 CEO Sergey Dmitriev was replaced by Oleg Stepanov and Maxim Shafirov.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2021 *The New York Times* stated that unknown parties might have embedded malware in JetBrains' TeamCity CI/CD software that led to the SolarWinds hack and other widespread security compromises.
[src:ktor/ktor] In a press release, JetBrains said they had not been contacted by any government or security agency and had not "taken part or been involved in this attack in any way".
[src:ktor/ktor] The CEO of one of the affected companies, SolarWinds, "asked about the possibility that software tools made by JetBrains, which speeds the development and testing of code, was the pathway".
[src:ktor/ktor] In response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, the company suspended sales and R&D activities in Russia indefinitely, as well as sales in Belarus.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains' Russian legal entity was liquidated on 21 February 2023.
[src:ktor/ktor] In September 2023, JetBrains acquired the company Code Buddy and its two main products, JPA Buddy and React Buddy.
[src:ktor/ktor] The tools were integrated into IntelliJ IDEA Ultimate and the team joined JetBrains to continue their development.
[src:ktor/ktor] Effective 1 February 2024, Kirill Skrygan replaced Maxim Shafirov as CEO.
[src:ktor/ktor] In December 2025, JetBrains unified IntelliJ IDEA into a single distribution, merging the previously separate Community Edition and Ultimate Edition.
[src:ktor/ktor] Under the new model, all Ultimate features require a subscription to unlock, while the IDE remains fully functional and free for both commercial and non-commercial projects without a subscription, including more features than the Community Edition previously offered.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains has achieved significant financial growth without external funding.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company reported 5.6% revenue growth in 2023, following 11% growth in 2022.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains is profitable with $200 million in EBITDA generated in 2020.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company has never raised external capital.
[src:ktor/ktor] The following is a non-exhaustive list of integrated development environments (IDEs) distributed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor/ktor] The JetBrains Marketplace offers 8,860 plugins that extend the functionality of JetBrains IDEs.
[src:ktor/ktor] ReSharper is a Visual Studio extension for .NET developers, first released in 2004.
[src:ktor/ktor] It is JetBrains' longest-standing commercial product and, according to JetBrains, has accumulated over 2.5 million downloads, making it the most popular extension on the Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:ktor/ktor] It was also a key revenue source for JetBrains in its early years.
[src:ktor/ktor] ReSharper provides on-the-fly code quality analysis for C#, VB.NET, XAML, ASP.NET, JavaScript, TypeScript, CSS, HTML, and XML.
[src:ktor/ktor] Its features include code refactoring, code completion, navigation, find usages, and code formatting.
[src:ktor/ktor] The extension offers more than 2,200 on-the-fly code inspections and over 60 refactorings and 450 context actions.
[src:ktor/ktor] Starting with version 2026.1, ReSharper expanded beyond Visual Studio to support Visual Studio Code and compatible editors such as Cursor, bringing JetBrains' C# tooling to a broader range of development environments.
[src:ktor/ktor] The VS Code extension provides real-time code analysis, refactorings, and navigation for C#, XAML, Razor, and Blazor, and includes a Solution Explorer as well as built-in unit testing support for NUnit, xUnit.net, and MSTest.
[src:ktor/ktor] ReSharper's development influenced the creation of JetBrains' standalone .NET IDE, Rider; although plans for a dedicated ReSharper IDE were explored and later abandoned after the release of Visual Studio 2005, the work done on ReSharper ultimately formed the foundation for Rider.
[src:ktor/ktor] ReSharper is available as a standalone license or as part of the dotUltimate subscription, which also includes Rider, dotTrace, dotCover, and dotMemory.
[src:ktor/ktor] Kotlin is an open-source, statically typed programming language that runs on the Java Virtual Machine and also compiles to JavaScript or native code (via LLVM).
