[src:ktor/ktor] In May 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android, and at Google I/O 2019, Google declared Kotlin its preferred language for Android app development.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains MPS is an open-source language workbench for domain-specific languages.
[src:ktor/ktor] Ktor is a Kotlin-based programming framework for developing "connected applications", using the same framework on both server (JVM) and client (JavaScript, Android, and iOS).
[src:ktor/ktor] Kotlin Multiplatform (KMP) is a JetBrains technology that allows developers to share Kotlin code across multiple platforms, including Android, iOS, desktop, web, and server.
[src:ktor/ktor] It reached stable status with the release of Kotlin 1.9.20 in November 2023.
[src:ktor/ktor] The related Compose Multiplatform framework, which enables shared user interfaces, became stable for iOS in 2025.
[src:ktor/ktor] TeamCity is a continuous integration and continuous delivery server developed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor/ktor] It is a server-based web application written in Java.
[src:ktor/ktor] *The New York Times* reported that TeamCity may have been used by Russian hackers of US governmental and private agencies, in potentially "the biggest breach of United States networks in history".
[src:ktor/ktor] Upsource was a code review and repository browsing tool supporting Git, GitHub, Mercurial, Perforce and/or Subversion repositories from a central location.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains released a new developer collaboration tool, Space, in 2019.
[src:ktor/ktor] It began sunsetting Upsource in 2022, officially ending support for the product in January 2023.
[src:ktor/ktor] In May 2024, JetBrains rebranded Space to SpaceCode to focus on Git hosting and code reviews.
[src:ktor/ktor] YouTrack is a proprietary, commercial web-based bug tracker, issue tracking system, and project management software developed by JetBrains.
[src:ktor/ktor] Qodana is a code quality analysis tool that uses static code analysis to help users with code reviews, building quality gates, and the implementation of code quality guidelines.
[src:ktor/ktor] It was publicly launched in July 2023 and can be used with IDEs in JetBrains's ecosystem, has CI/CD pipeline integration, while supporting code analysis in over 60 programming languages.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains AI Assistant is offered in most JetBrains IDEs as a set of AI-assisted software development tools.
[src:ktor/ktor] The assistant uses models from OpenAI and Google, as well as proprietary models developed by JetBrains, such as the Mellum model released in April 2025.
[src:ktor/ktor] Junie is an AI coding agent developed by JetBrains, launched in January 2025 in closed preview.
[src:ktor/ktor] Unlike the AI Assistant, which focuses on code completion, Junie is designed to function as an AI agent for coding.
[src:ktor/ktor] In April 2025, JetBrains made Junie generally available.
[src:ktor/ktor] Datalore is a web application for data analysis and visualization, which is focused specifically on the machine learning environment in Python.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains Academy is an online platform to learn programming, including such programming languages as Python, Java, and Kotlin.
[src:ktor/ktor] The Academy was introduced by JetBrains in 2019, and reached 200,000 users by July 2020.
[src:ktor/ktor] Certifications were added in November 2021 after community feedback prioritized verifiability of the work done on projects.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains has also developed the EduTools plugin for students, which is compatible with IntelliJ IDEA (Ultimate, Community, Educational), Android Studio, CLion, GoLand, PhpStorm, PyCharm (Professional, Community, Educational), WebStorm.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2009, JetBrains open-sourced the core functionality of IntelliJ IDEA by offering the free Community Edition.
[src:ktor/ktor] It is built on the IntelliJ Platform and includes its sources.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains released both under Apache License 2.0.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2010, Android support became a part of the Community Edition, and two years later Google announced its Android Studio, the IDE for mobile development on Android platform built on the Community Edition of IntelliJ IDEA and an official alternative to Eclipse Android Developer Tool.
[src:ktor/ktor] After two years of development JetBrains open-sourced Kotlin in February 2012.
[src:ktor/ktor] In June 2015, it was announced that the support of Eclipse ADT would be discontinued, making Android Studio the official tool for Android App development.
[src:ktor/ktor] In January 2020, JetBrains released a geometric monospaced font called JetBrains Mono, made the default font for its IDEs, under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:ktor/ktor] The font is designed for reading source code by being optimized for reading vertically with support for programming ligatures.
[src:ktor/ktor] As a private company, JetBrains does not disclose detailed financial statements.
[src:ktor/ktor] However, its annual highlight reports indicate consistent growth.
[src:ktor/ktor] In its 2023 highlights, the company reported a 5.6% year-over-year revenue growth and noted 11.4 million recurring active users.
[src:ktor/ktor] This followed an 11% revenue growth in 2022, when the company reported having 15.9 million users.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company's business model is primarily based on software subscriptions.
[src:ktor/ktor] In recent years, JetBrains has adjusted its model in response to market trends.
[src:ktor/ktor] This includes making more of its IDEs available with free, non-commercial licenses, such as for RustRover, and unifying its flagship IDE, IntelliJ IDEA, to offer a single download with both free and paid features.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains maintains partnerships with more than 140 resellers and numerous technology partners worldwide.
[src:ktor/ktor] According to partnership data, JetBrains has 49 partners, including 41 technology partners and 8 channel partners, with Salesforce as its largest partner.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains has an active technology partnership with Google Cloud.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2022, the companies partnered to deliver integration between Google Cloud Workstations and JetBrains remote development, allowing developers to use JetBrains IDEs with Google Cloud's managed development environments.
[src:ktor/ktor] This integration gave Cloud Workstations support for popular JetBrains IDEs such as IntelliJ IDEA, PyCharm, and Rider, allowing developers to take advantage of managed and customizable environments in Google Cloud within their preferred IDE.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2024, JetBrains extended its collaboration with Google Cloud to integrate Google's Gemini models into JetBrains AI Assistant, making it the first tool of its kind to combine functionality from OpenAI's GPT-4o, Gemini, and JetBrains' proprietary models.
[src:ktor/ktor] The collaboration leveraged Google Cloud's Vertex AI to expand the pool of large language models (LLMs) available to AI Assistant users, with Gemini Pro 1.5 and Flash 1.5 adding a long context window, advanced reasoning, and high-volume, low-latency capabilities.
[src:ktor/ktor] With JetBrains AI Enterprise, organisations were given the ability to configure which LLM their teams use, while for other users the assistant automatically selects the most suitable model for each task.
[src:ktor/ktor] Later that year, starting from version 2024.3 of JetBrains AI Assistant, users were able to select their preferred LLM directly within the AI chat interface.
[src:ktor/ktor] The partnership further expanded in 2025, when JetBrains integrated Gemini 3 Pro into both its AI Assistant and its AI coding agent Junie, with JetBrains noting that the new model showed more than a 50% improvement over Gemini 2.5 Pro in solved benchmark tasks.
[src:ktor/ktor] Google Cloud also made Gemini Code Assist available as a plugin for JetBrains IDEs, supporting real-time code completions, full-function generation, and natural-language-to-code conversion within the JetBrains ecosystem.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains participates in various strategic collaborations, including the Java Community Process Executive Committee, Kotlin Foundation, and supports JUnit 5.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company also partners with Unity for RiderFlow and GitLab to optimize review experiences.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains provides extensive support to educational institutions and the developer community.
[src:ktor/ktor] In 2024, 1,840,580 students and 94,041 teachers benefited from complimentary JetBrains educational packs, while 954,277 students received special discounts for license renewal upon graduation.
[src:ktor/ktor] Additionally, 2,172 schools and universities received 190,459 educational subscriptions for classroom assistance, and 26,100 students from 596 training courses and boot camps received free subscriptions.
[src:ktor/ktor] The company supports the open source community with 5,952 projects receiving 11,364 complimentary licenses.
[src:ktor/ktor] Through the User Group Support Program, 611 tech communities from 89 countries and regions obtained 3,916 licenses.
[src:ktor/ktor] The Developer Recognition Program honored 1,284 community experts with complimentary All Products Pack subscriptions.
[src:ktor/ktor] Additionally, 12,615 customers benefited from the Startup discount, and JetBrains sponsored 155 IT events.
[src:ktor/ktor] JetBrains conducts annual Developer Ecosystem surveys to understand industry trends.
[src:ktor/ktor] The 2024 survey was based on input from 23,262 developers and provides insights into programming language usage, development practices, and industry trends.
